flow. Finishing the animation code...\n\nThe console and travel fade operate independently—the console disappears after 0.15 seconds while the main fade-out continues for 0.5 seconds, so the timing should work cleanly without conflicts.\n\nI'm wondering if `process_mode` could be interfering. The NavigationConsole inherits the default mode, and while `InputManager.set_gameplay_inputs_enabled(false)` disables player input, it shouldn't affect UI processing. I think I've found the issue, so let me move forward with that theory.\n\nAfter digging through this, I suspect the problem is either an execution order conflict causing the travel sequence to fail silently, or a visual conflict between the panel close animation and the travel fade. But actually, I just caught something crucial I overlooked — let me check `_on_confirm_pressed` again...\n\nChecking the confirm handler...\n\nWhat if `_is_open` is already false when `close_panel()` gets called? That would cause an early return and prevent the rest of the cleanup. Though that shouldn't happen since `open_panel()` sets it to true, and GDScript is single-threaded so there's no race condition. Let me trace through the actual execution flow more carefully.\n\nNow I'm looking at the input handler when focus is on the buttons rather than the map. When the player presses up or left, focus shifts back to the map and the visuals update. Pressing down moves focus between the confirm and cancel buttons, and pressing accept triggers the confirm button if it has focus and isn't disabled.\n\nThe real question is whether the confirm button actually has focus when the player reaches it, since that's what determines whether pressing enter executes the confirmation or closes the panel instead.\n\nWhen the player presses down from the map, the code calls `grab_focus()` on the confirm button, which should work fine in Godot 4 regardless of how deeply nested it is in the UI hierarchy. But something might be stealing focus between that moment and when the player presses enter—like the `_update_map_visuals()` call that happens during input processing.\n\nActually, wait. Let me step back and look at this more fundamentally. The symptom is that pressing the button does nothing at all—no transition, no error, nothing. That suggests the button's `pressed` signal might not even be connected in the first place, which would be a much more basic issue than focus handling.\n\nSetting up the button...\n\nNow I'm tracing through the input flow for mouse clicks. In Godot 4, when you click the mouse, the event goes through the viewport's GUI layer first, which finds the Control under the cursor and processes it. I need to figure out if something in that chain is breaking the signal connection or preventing the button from receiving the input event. a Control handles the event, it's marked as handled\n4. Then `_input()` runs (but the event might already be handled)\n5. Then `_unhandled_input()`\n\nWait, I think I was wrong before. In Godot 4:\n- Mouse click events are FIRST processed by the viewport for GUI controls\n- If a Control processes the event (by calling `accept_event()` or by having MOUSE_FILTER_STOP), the event is marked as handled for `_input()` purposes\n- But `_input()` still receives the event unless the viewport is configured otherwise\n\nActually, in Godot 4, the exact behavior depends on the viewport settings. By default:\n1. `_input()` runs first for all nodes\n2. Then GUI input processing happens\n3. Then `_unhandled_input()`\n\nIf `_input()` calls `set_input_as_handled()`, GUI processing is skipped.\n\nSo the actual order in Godot 4.x is: `_input()` fires first in reverse tree order, then the viewport dispatches to GUI controls, then `_shortcut_input()`, and finally `_unhandled_input()`. This means the NavigationConsole's `_input()` handler would intercept the mouse click before any GUI processing happens. When checking the event, it would test for ui_cancel and other actions, then evaluate the