low, `add_child()` is called before `setup()`, so the node should already be in the tree when `_build_fade_overlay()` executes. The fade overlay should exist, the tween should work, and the biome swap should happen. I'm completely stuck on what's actually preventing this from working.\n\nLet me trace through the `_on_travel_completed` handler one more time to see what's actually happening when the travel sequence starts.\n\nI'm realizing there's a potential issue with the `_is_transitioning` flag — it guards against the handler being called while a transition is already in progress, but what if the signal itself gets connected multiple times? If `travel_completed` is somehow wired up twice, the second invocation would hit the early return and never complete the biome swap.\n\nLet me refocus on the actual problem though: the simplest explanation is that the button press is firing but silently exiting through one of the guard clauses, most likely because no biome is selected or the fuel check is failing. 2. `not NavigationSystem.can_travel_to(_selected_biome_id)` — returns if can't afford\n\nFor #1: The biome must be selected for the button to be enabled. If the button is enabled, a biome is selected. So this guard should pass.\n\nFor #2: `can_travel_to` was true when the button was enabled. Could it become false between button enable and button click?\n\nThe button is enabled in `_refresh_detail()`. The user then clicks the button. Between these events:\n- `_on_fuel_changed` might fire (if fuel changes), calling `_refresh_detail()` which might re-disable the button. But fuel doesn't change passively.\n- No other code modifies the fuel state.\n\nSo `can_travel_to` should still be true. The guard passes.\n\nThen `initiate_travel` is called. It also checks `can_travel_to` with the same result.\n\nEverything should work. But wait—what if the InputManager is the culprit? When `open_panel()` calls `InputManager.set_gameplay_inputs_enabled(false)`, it might disable input processing entirely, which could prevent the NavigationConsole's `_input()` handler from running at all. If that's the case, keyboard navigation wouldn't work even if the button state logic is sound.\n\nBut the user can navigate to the button and select a biome, so `_input()` must be working. Unless `InputManager.set_gameplay_inputs_enabled(false)` only blocks specific input actions, not all input—in which case navigation works but the button's `pressed` signal doesn't fire. Actually, no—the `pressed` signal is a GUI signal, not an input action, so it shouldn't be affected by InputManager at all.\n\nI should check the InputManager and FuelSystem code directly to understand what's happening. There's also a possibility the biome transition actually does occur (fuel consumed, biome changed) but the TravelSequenceManager's visual feedback isn't displaying properly.\n\nChecking the `execute_biome_swap` function to see if it's failing silently...\n\nExamining the biome creation logic...\n\nActually, I'm wondering if the issue is with the NavigationConsole's CanvasLayer and how it's handling visibility or input blocking during the transition.\n\nLet me step back and look at what's actually happening: the button is clickable and enabled, but pressing it produces no visible effect—no fade, no transition sequence starting. That suggests the button press itself isn't triggering the expected chain of events.\n\nThe core issue is either the `_on_confirm_pressed` callback isn't being invoked at all, or it's returning early before anything visible happens. The `_input` handler doesn't intercept mouse clicks, so the GUI should receive the event normally and fire the signal.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":31,"cache_read_input_tokens":67582,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":31},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_