n is already happening and bails out if so, then disables gameplay inputs before fading out and executing the biome swap. The issue is that `close_panel()` also manipulates input state, so there's a race condition where both functions are trying to control input handling at the same time. 3. `TravelSequenceManager._on_travel_completed()` is called, starts the transition with `await _fade_out()`\n4. Since `_fade_out()` uses `await`, the `_on_travel_completed` function suspends\n5. Control returns to `initiate_travel()` which finishes\n6. Control returns to `_on_confirm_pressed()` which calls `close_panel()`\n\nSo the flow should actually work! The `travel_completed` signal fires, `TravelSequenceManager` starts its async transition, and control returns to the caller.\n\nWhen a signal emits in GDScript and a connected method contains `await`, that method runs synchronously until it hits the await point, then control returns to the emitter. So `_on_travel_completed()` sets the transition flag and disables inputs, then suspends at `await _fade_out()` while the tween animates. Meanwhile, `initiate_travel()` continues logging the arrival and returns to `_on_confirm_pressed()`, which closes the panel—all before the fade animation completes.\n\nBut the user says pressing CONFIRM TRAVEL does nothing. Let me check if `_on_confirm_pressed` is actually being called. The button connection looks right, and the `_input()` method should be routing the input correctly...\n\nActually, I need to trace through what happens when `_on_confirm_pressed` executes. There are two early returns that could prevent the travel from initiating: either the selected biome ID is empty, or the navigation system says travel isn't possible. Let me check which one might be blocking it.\n\nThe button gets enabled in `_refresh_detail()` based on whether `NavigationSystem.can_travel_to()` returns true, so unless something changed between that check and the actual click, that shouldn't be the blocker. But I should also verify that the `setup()` method is properly initializing all the required state that these checks depend on. Let me trace through the confirm flow again with fresh eyes. When `_on_confirm_pressed()` fires, it emits the `travel_confirmed` signal (which nothing listens to), calls `NavigationSystem.initiate_travel()` to emit `travel_completed`, and then `TravelSequenceManager._on_travel_completed()` should handle the actual sequence.\n\nThat handler sets input disabled, starts the fade out, and waits for it to complete before swapping biomes and fading back in. Meanwhile, `close_panel()` re-enables input and hides the panel, which would undo the input disable that just happened. The biome swap itself should work fine, but the input state gets tangled up.\n\nThe real question is whether `_fade_out()` actually completes...\n\nExamining the fade function... The user is saying the button press does nothing, which means either the callback isn't firing, there's an early return, or the navigation system itself isn't working. Let me trace through `_on_confirm_pressed()` — it checks if a biome is selected and if travel is allowed, then emits a signal and calls the navigation system. The function appears to be cut off mid-call, but I'm trying to figure out where the chain breaks.\n\nI'm noticing the button's disabled state might be preventing the signal from firing at all, and now I'm wondering if there's a mouse event issue with the button being nested inside a ScrollContainer, which could be intercepting clicks.\n\nThe keyboard path through `_input()` should work when the button has focus and isn't disabled, but I'm starting to suspect the real problem might be that `NavigationSystem` isn't properly initialized as an autoload singleton, which would explain why the travel call isn't going through.\n\nLet me trace through the button creation itself to see if there's something preventing the `pressed` signal from firing in the first place. I'm wondering if the real issue is in the `_input()` handler itself. Let me trace through what happens when the confirm button should be clickable — I'm checking if the focus is on the map and whether the ui_accept action properly triggers the button selection logic. I'm noticing a potential issue with the input handling flow. When the map has focus and the user presses accept, it selects the biome and shifts focus to the confirm button, which works fine. But then on the next accept press, the code checks if the confirm button has focus and isn't disabled before calling the confirm action. This should work for keyboard input, and mouse clicks should trigger the signal directly. Let me trace through the mouse click path to see if there's something I'm missing there.\n\nThe confirm button is nested inside a ScrollContainer, which in Godot can sometimes interfere with mouse events by capturing them at the scrollbar or container level. But actually, I think the real issue might be simpler—maybe `_on_confirm_pressed` is executing but hitting an early return silently. Looking at the function, it checks if the selected biome ID is empty or if travel isn't allowed to that biome, and either of those conditions would cause it to return without doing anything visible.\n\nThe problem could be that `NavigationSystem.can_travel_to()` returns false when the button is clicked, even though it returned true when the detail panel was last refreshed. The function calculates distance and ship weight, then checks if fuel is sufficient for that distance—so if the ship's state changed between the refresh and the click, the travel check would fail silently.\n\nLooking at the producer notes, the button does enable correctly (so `can_travel_to` passes during `_refresh_detail`), but pressing it produces no response at all. That suggests the travel check is failing at click time, not at enable time.\n\nI'm wondering if there's a race condition where `close_panel()` re-enables input handling and captures the mouse, which might be interrupting the fade-out animation in `TravelSequenceManager`. But actually, tracing through `_on_confirm_pressed()` more carefully: when it calls `NavigationSystem.initiate_travel()`, the entire state machine runs synchronously in one frame—transitioning through PREPARING, IN_TRANSIT, ARRIVING, updating the biome, and back to IDLE, then emitting `travel_completed`. So if nothing's happening, the travel initiation itself must be failing silently. - this triggers `_on_travel_completed`\n   - In `_on_travel_completed`:\n     - Sets `_is_transitioning = true`\n     - Emits `travel_sequence_started` (which sets `_transitioning = true` in TestWorld)\n     - Disables input\n     - Starts `_fade_out()` and **awaits** - control returns to `initiate_travel`\n   - Emits `biome_changed(destination_id)` - nobody seems to connect to this...\n   - Logs arrival\n3. Back in `_on_confirm_pressed()`, `close_panel()` is called\n4. `close_panel()` re-enables input via `InputManager.set_gameplay_inputs_enabled(true)`\n5. Later, `_fade_out()` completes, `_on_travel_completed` resumes with `execute_biome_swap(destination_id)` which should do the actual swap\n\nSo the biome swap should happen unless `_fade_out()` never completes. Let me check if `close_panel()` somehow destroys the tween. Looking at `_animate_close()`, it creates its own tween that fades out the panel and dim rect over 0.15 seconds, then hides the panel—this shouldn't interfere with the fade out tween running in parallel.\n\nActually, I'm wondering if the transition is working but just not visible—maybe the fade to black and back happens, the biome swaps, but the new biome looks identical or the player ends up in the same visual spot. But the producer said there's no visible response at all, so that doesn't quite fit.\n\nLet me trace through what happens if `_fade_rect` is null. The fade-out function would return early without awaiting anything, so execution would immediately jump to the biome swap and then fade-