nough to display it.\n\nLet me trace through what happens when the confirm button is pressed: it emits the `travel_confirmed` signal, calls `NavigationSystem.initiate_travel()` which runs the state machine synchronously and emits `travel_completed`, then closes the panel. The `TravelSequenceManager` picks up that completion signal and starts the async transition. Everything looks wired correctly, so maybe the problem is something simpler like the button not being initialized properly or the panel not being set up right.\n\nActually, wait—I'm looking at the early-return conditions in `initiate_travel`. If the state isn't IDLE, the method just silently returns without doing anything. If a previous travel attempt failed and left the state stuck in PREPARING or IN_TRANSIT, then any new travel attempts would be completely ignored. That could explain why the producer can press the button but nothing happens.\n\nBut this is a fresh game start, so the state should definitely be IDLE. And `destination_id == current_biome` would only be true if the biome was already set to the destination, which doesn't make sense for a fresh start.\n\nLet me think about this differently. When the button is pressed and nothing happens, the issue could be one of a few things: the click handler itself isn't being triggered, `initiate_travel` is silently returning due to one of those guard conditions, the travel transition is running but visually invisible, or an error is occurring somewhere but getting swallowed. I should check how the button is actually connected to the travel logic.\n\nThe button's styling method only handles visual overrides, not input handling. The default mouse filter and focus mode should allow clicks to work fine. I remember checking the focus mode earlier and seeing it set to FOCUS_NONE, but that was for the biome node buttons' overlay, not the confirm button itself. Let me trace through the actual call chain again and verify the NavigationSystem autoload is working correctly.\n\nActually, I'm wondering if the button itself works but something in the UI hierarchy is blocking mouse events — maybe the ScrollContainer's scrollbar or another element is intercepting clicks. Let me check the full signal chain from button press through to the biome transition, and examine whether there's a mouse event handling issue within the ScrollContainer. The NavigationConsole is a CanvasLayer with a Control that has MOUSE_FILTER_STOP...\n\nNow I'm tracing through the node hierarchy to see where the CONFIRM TRAVEL button sits — it's nested inside a ScrollContainer on the right side of the panel, and when a click happens, the event needs to propagate through all these layers without being blocked.\n\nThe ScrollContainer has mouse_filter set to MOUSE_FILTER_STOP by default, which means it processes events but doesn't block children from receiving them, so the Button should still get clicked. Since the Button also has MOUSE_FILTER_STOP, it should handle the click and trigger `_on_confirm_pressed`.\n\nI can't find a code-level reason why the button wouldn't respond to clicks, so maybe the callback is actually being called but the transition happens so quickly or gets immediately reverted that it's invisible to the user.\n\nWhen the confirm button is pressed, it emits the signal, initiates travel through the state machine, closes the panel, and then asynchronously swaps the biome by clearing the old one and creating a new one with repositioned player and ship. This should definitely be visible unless `create_biome_node` is returning null because the biome_id doesn't match any of the hardcoded cases, even though \"rock_warrens\" should match.\n\nLooking at how biome IDs flow through the system—they come from `BiomeRegistry.BIOME_IDS` and get passed through `_select_biome()` to `_selected_biome_id`—the format should be consistent. The logic seems sound, so this might be something more subtle or environmental.\n\nHold on, let me trace through `_on_confirm_pressed()` more carefully. The function checks if the selected biome ID is empty and whether travel is allowed before emitting the signal and initiating travel. But what if `can_travel_to()` is returning false even though the button was enabled? Maybe something else changed between when the button was enabled and when confirm was pressed—not just fuel, but some other condition that `can_travel_to()` checks.\n\nActually, I'm noticing that `_on_confirm_pressed()` gets called from two different sources: the button's `pressed` signal from a mouse click, and the `_input()` handler when the ui_accept action is triggered. Let me think about whether one of these paths might be failing.\n\nThe `_input()` handler marks events as handled, but that shouldn't interfere with the button's normal GUI processing. A mouse click wouldn't trigger `ui_cancel` or the directional inputs, so it shouldn't be getting consumed by the input handler either.\n\nLet me trace through `_on_confirm_pressed` to check for any silent failures—`_selected_biome_id` should be set from `_select_biome`, and the calls to `NavigationSystem` and `close_panel()` should all execute without issues.\n\nNow I'm checking the `initiate_travel` method for potential problems: `_state` starts as IDLE, the biome validation and fuel consumption should work, and both the `travel_completed` and `biome_changed` signals should emit correctly.\n\nMoving into `_on_travel_completed`, I'm verifying that `_is_transitioning` is properly initialized, the input manager call disables gameplay inputs, and then `_fade_out()` and `execute_biome_swap()` should execute in sequence.\n\nWait—what if the travel IS actually happening (fuel gets consumed, biome state updates), but the visual transition stalls because the await in `_on_travel_completed` never resolves? The real culprit might be the TravelSequenceManager's process mode. In Godot 4, if a node's process mode is disabled or set to pause-only while the game isn't paused, its tweens won't advance. Something could be preventing this node from processing.\n\nI'm wondering if `InputManager.set_gameplay_inputs_enabled(false)` does more than just toggle inputs—maybe it affects the scene tree's pause state or process modes. Though looking at the name, it probably just manages input actions. And even if there was a process mode issue, calling `set_gameplay_inputs_enabled(true)` right after in `close_panel()` would reverse it immediately.\n\nBut here's the thing—the fade-out tween might have already been created before the process mode gets restored.\n\nLet me trace through the exact sequence: `_on_confirm_pressed` triggers `initiate_travel`, which synchronously emits `travel_completed`, calling `_on_travel_completed`. That sets `_is_transitioning = true`, emits `travel_sequence_started` (which sets `_transitioning = true` in TestWorld), disables inputs, and then creates the fade-out tween.\n\nThe tween starts the fade animation and suspends at `await tween.finished`, so control returns to `initiate_travel` which continues with `biome_changed.emit()` and logging. Then `initiate_travel` returns, `close_panel()` gets called, which disables the panel, re-enables inputs, captures the mouse, animates the panel closed, and emits `panel_closed`.\n\nAfter 0.5 seconds when the fade finishes, `_on_travel_completed` resumes and executes the biome swap, fades back in, re-enables inputs again, sets `_is_transitioning` to false, and emits `travel_sequence_completed` so TestWorld knows the transition is done. The logic should work, though there's a minor input state race condition at the close_panel step that's cosmetic rather than breaking anything.\n\nNow I'm trying to figure out what might have changed in the previous commit that could be affecting this flow.\n\nThe last fix was about fuel calculation — it modified how `calculate_ship_weight()` works to use a base weight and exclude inventory items. That shouldn't impact the travel sequence at all. But let me think about whether `consume_fuel` could be leaving the fuel in a bad state that makes `can_travel_to` fail on the second check in `_on_confirm_pressed`. Actually, that doesn't track — the button wouldn't be enabled if `can_travel_to` returned false, and the fuel state hasn't changed between the button enable and the click.\n\nI think I need to actually test this to see what's happening.\n\nLet me look at `close_panel()` to see if something there might be interfering with the travel setup. The function re-enables gameplay inputs, resets the mouse mode, animates the panel closing, and emits a `panel_closed` signal. I should check what's listening to that signal in TestWorld.\n\nI don't see anything connected to `panel_closed`, so that's not the issue. Let me trace whether the confirm button is actually reachable by mouse clicks given the nested hierarchy and mouse filter settings in the CanvasLayer.\n\nIn Godot 4, containers default to MOUSE_FILTER_STOP, which means they consume clicks but pass them to children—so the click should propagate down through the hierarchy to the button. The button itself has a custom minimum size of 240x52, so it should have a proper clickable rect. At this point the code looks correct, but there might be something subtle I'm missing that requires testing rather than code inspection.\n\nThe most likely culprits are that the button press is actually firing but the visual feedback is too quick to notice, there's a runtime error I can't see from the code, or the tween's finished signal isn't firing properly. Let me check if `_biome_container` might be null when `execute_biome_swap` gets called after the await completes.\n\nLooking at how the biome container gets passed through the setup chain — it's created as a new Node3D in `_build_biome_content()`, then passed to the travel manager's setup method. So the reference should be valid unless something's clearing it between setup and the swap execution.\n\nI think I've been overthinking this. The real issue is probably that when the player confirms travel while inside the ship interior at Y=-50, the repositioning logic isn't accounting for that. The biome swap moves everything to the new spawn points, but if the player is underground in the ship interior rather than at the exterior spawn point, they might end up in the wrong place or not see the transition at all. Let me check what `_reposition_at_spawn` actually does...\n\nAh, I see the problem now. The function repositions the player to the biome's exterior spawn point on the surface, but the ship interior stays at its Y offset underground. So the player gets teleported from inside the ship to the surface, which breaks the expected behavior. The ship interior stays at Y=-50 as a direct child of TestWorld, separate from the biome content that gets swapped out. So when the player is underground in the ship interior and the biome swap happens, they're not seeing the new ground or boundaries because those are being replaced while the player remains in the old underground space — nothing visually changes from their perspective.\n\nThe fade animation should still be visible on the CanvasLayer, but I'm wondering if the NavigationConsole's close animation is somehow blocking or interfering with the fade effect since it's on a lower layer.\n\nActually, I need to verify that the fade overlay is properly added to the scene tree — the TravelSequenceManager gets added to TestWorld during setup, and the fade overlay is created as a child of TravelSequenceManager, so it should render correctly on layer 10.\n\nBut if the producer sees nothing happening at all, that suggests the fade isn't triggering, which means `_on_travel_completed` probably isn't being called. Let me trace through the signal connection — I'm creating the TravelSequenceManager, adding it as a child, then calling setup on it, which is where the signal should be connected.\n\nActually, wait — I need to verify that NavigationSystem is properly set up as an autoload. The script has the right class name, and the navigation console is already using it successfully with methods like `current_biome` and `can_travel_to()`, so the autoload itself should be working fine.\n\nThe signal connection looks correct too. But the user said \"no error\" when they pressed the button, which means they checked the output log and found nothing — so it's not a runtime error or null reference issue.\n\nWhen they say \"no visible response,\" they probably mean the biome didn't transition, even though the panel might have closed. And \"no biome transition\" suggests the player stayed in the same location. I'm wondering if the biome actually swapped but they can't see it because they're still inside the ship interior underground. The fade overlay should still trigger though, unless there's an issue with how the `_fade_rect` is anchored within the CanvasLayer.\n\nActually, setting the anchors to cover the full rect on a CanvasLayer child should work correctly since CanvasLayer children use the viewport's dimensions. So that's probably not the culprit. Let me stop theorizing and focus on the actual problem — it's most likely that the coroutine is failing silently, or the transition is happening but invisible to the player while they're in the ship interior.\n\nLooking at the actual flow, I see a real bug: when the navigation console confirms travel, it emits the signal, initiates the travel sequence, then immediately calls `close_panel()` which re-enables gameplay inputs. But the TravelSequenceManager just disabled those inputs, so we're fighting against each other. More critically, closing the panel during an active travel transition could be interrupting the whole sequence.\n\nBut there's another angle I should consider — what if the callback is connected but the tween itself is getting killed? In Godot 4, tweens are bound to their node, so if the node's processing gets paused or the tree state changes, the tween stops. The TravelSequenceManager inherits its process mode by default, so if InputManager is changing process modes when it disables inputs, that could be silently killing the tween without any errors.\n\nLet me also check if the confirm button is actually being interacted with. The button gets created and added to the detail column, but I should verify it's not hidden or disabled when the user tries to click it. Looking at the refresh logic, the button gets disabled when no biome is selected, but when one is selected...\n\nStill examining the confirm handler...\n\nI see the issue now — `close_panel()` gets called right after `initiate_travel()`, which means inputs are re-enabled before the fade-out animation completes. When `_on_travel_completed` eventually resumes from its await, the biome container should still exist since it's part of TestWorld, but the timing of when things get cleaned up versus when the panel closes could be causing the button state to get out of sync. Let me map out the actual sequence of events and identify which fix would be most practical. Let me trace through what happens when the button is clicked. The `_input` handler in NavigationConsole checks for keyboard actions like `ui_cancel`, `ui_up`, `ui_left`, `ui_down`, and `ui_accept`, but a mouse click doesn't match any of these — so the input handler ignores it and the click propagates normally to the button's `pressed` signal. That means the button should be receiving the click and firing the callback.\n\nBut I'm realizing the `dim_layer` Control might be the culprit here. It has `mouse_filter = Control.MOUSE_FILTER_STOP`, which means it's actively consuming mouse events instead of letting them pass through to the button underneath. I'm wondering if another Control node might be sitting on top of the button and blocking the click. The disabled reason label is hidden when fuel is sufficient, so that's not it. The ScrollContainer's scrollbars shouldn't be in the way either since horizontal scrolling is disabled and the vertical bar only appears on overflow. But I should verify whether the button might be positioned outside the ScrollContainer's visible clipping area.\n\nLooking at what fills the detail column—fuel info, load button, destination details, and the confirm button at the bottom—there's quite a bit of content stacking up. The ScrollContainer expands to fill available vertical space in the layout, but with a 600-pixel panel height minus the title bar and other UI elements, I need to calculate whether the confirm button actually fits within the visible bounds.\n\nThe producer can see and interact with the button since they mentioned pressing it, so visibility isn't the issue. My focus should shift to what happens when the button is actually clicked—likely the `_on_confirm_pressed` method isn't executing properly or is silently failing.\n\nLooking at the signal connections, I notice the NavigationConsole emits `travel_confirmed` but TestWorld doesn't listen to it, which means the actual travel logic must be handled elsewhere through NavigationSystem. Let me trace through what happens when the confirm button is pressed to see where the chain breaks. I'm seeing the rest of the `initiate_travel` method now—it validates the destination, checks fuel availability, and emits `travel_blocked` if there's insufficient fuel before proceeding to set the state and prepare for travel.\n\nNow I'm handling the actual state transitions: calculating the travel cost, consuming fuel, moving through the PREPARING, IN_TRANSIT, and ARRIVING states, then updating the current biome and firing the completion signals with a log message.\n\nLooking at the state machine, I realize the travel signal only fails to emit if one of those early returns triggers, which shouldn't happen if the button is enabled. But what if the state somehow isn't IDLE when the confirm button is pressed? Tracing through the transitions—initialization sets it to IDLE, `initiate_travel` cycles through all states back to IDLE, and `reset` also returns to IDLE—the only way it could get stuck is if a previous travel call didn't complete the full cycle.\n\nSince all the state transitions are synchronous within the same function, the state should always return to IDLE after completion, even if there are errors during fuel consumption or other operations. GDScript doesn't halt execution on errors, so the transitions would still finish.\n\nI think the real issue is that `_on_confirm_pressed` is probably being called and working fine, but the visual feedback or the signal callback isn't actually triggering. Let me verify whether the `_on_travel_completed` callback in TravelSequenceManager is actually being invoked by checking if the signal connection is properly set up.\n\nActually, I'm wondering if there's a simpler explanation: what if `_on_confirm_pressed` is only being called through the keyboard input path and not through the button's pressed signal? Looking at the input handler, it checks if the confirm button has focus before calling the method, and it sets the input as handled afterward.\n\nFor mouse clicks, the button's pressed signal should fire normally through the GUI system. But for keyboard input, `_input` gets called first and consumes the event before the button's built-in handler can respond — except the code explicitly calls `_on_confirm_pressed` anyway, so that should still work. The real question is whether there's a priority issue where the input is being consumed at the wrong point in the event chain.\n\nBoth the keyboard and mouse paths should be triggering the travel logic, so maybe the issue is actually downstream in FuelSystem or the consume_fuel method itself.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":29,"cache_read_input_tokens":67613,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":29},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_ma